# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-butter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-butter/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:apple-butter/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:apple-butter/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:apple-butter/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:apple-butter/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:apple-butter/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:apple-butter/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:apple-butter/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:apple-butter/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:apple-butter/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:apple-butter/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:apple-butter/airlie-red-flesh] Oregon apple with bright pink flesh and speckled green skin.
[src:apple-butter/airlie-red-flesh] The **Airlie Red Flesh**, (also known as the **Hidden Rose** or the **Mountain Rose**), is a cultivar of domesticated apple.
[src:apple-butter/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh tree will grow to a height of 4 meters (13 ft) to 5 meters (16 ft), and starts to fruit after about 4 years of growing.
[src:apple-butter/airlie-red-flesh] Airlie Red Flesh fruits are medium-sized, often small.
[src:apple-butter/airlie-red-flesh] The flavour of an Airlie Red Flesh apple has a balance of sweetness and tartness.
[src:apple-butter/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple has dark red flesh and a crisp texture.
[src:apple-butter/airlie-red-flesh] The Airlie Red Flesh apple tends to ripen in late September.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] '**Akane'**, also known as '**Tokyo Rose'**, '**Tohoku No.3'** and '**Prime Red'**, is a Japanese cultivar of domesticated apple, that according to Orange Pippin is one of the best early season apples.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] 'Akane' was developed by the Morika Experimental Station of Japan sometime between 1900 and 1949, by crossing a Jonathan apple with a Worcester Pearmain, and was introduced to the United States in 1937, where it is very popular.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] 'Akane' is of moderately good disease resistance, best at warm climates but tolerates cold also.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] It flowers mid-late season, and should be harvested early-mid season.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] It is self-sterile and needs to be cross pollinated.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] It produces heavy crop of variable sized fruits, usually more to the smaller side, but good sized apples can be obtained by thinning.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] 'Akane' carries the fruit shape of the English 'Worcester Pearmain', and the unusually good balanced flavor of the 'Jonathan'.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] Shape ranges from flattened to heart-shaped.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] Fruits have a very good flavor, a blend of sweet and sharp, preferable for eating, keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] Flesh color is white, with a yellow tinge.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] The apple is crisp, but not too dense; it is easy to eat.
[src:apple-butter/akane-apple] The fruit keeps fresh for about one week.
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] '**Alkmene'** is a German cultivar of domesticated apple, also called '**Early Windsor'**.
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] Two natural mutations (sports) of this cultivar that have red-skinned fruit have been selected: one called '**Red Alkmene'** was trademarked under the name of **Red Windsor**; the other is '**Ceeval'**.
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] It was developed between 1900 and 1949, by the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute in Müncheberg, Germany, by crossing the two cultivars 'Cox's Orange Pippin' and 'Geheimrat Dr.
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] Oldenburg' (frequently confused with the similar-sounding 'Duchess of Oldenburg').
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] The result is an early harvest apple (early mid season), which is very attractive, with a honeyed flavor similar to Cox's but slightly sharper.
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' flowers early mid season, with self-fertile blossoms, hence no cross pollination is needed.
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] Fruit size is medium and variable, flesh color is yellowish or extremely yellow for an apple, skin has greenish-yellow background with orange-reddish flush and strong red strips.
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] The 'Red Windsor' cultivar has a larger portion of red.
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] It is resistant to apple scab and susceptible to blossom frost.
[src:apple-butter/alkmene-apple] 'Alkmene' was awarded the Award of Garden Merit by the Royal Horticultural Society in 1998.
[src:apple-butter/allington-pippin] '**Allington Pippin'** is an English cultivar of domesticated apple, with a strong flavour that includes hints of pineapple.
[src:apple-butter/allington-pippin] The Allington Pippin was developed prior to year 1884 by Thomas Laxton in Lincolnshire, England through a cross breeding of Cox's Orange Pippin and the King of the Pippins.
[src:apple-butter/allington-pippin] This name was not given until 1894, when George Bunyard named it after the village of Allington near Maidstone in Kent, where one of the Bunyard's nurseries was situated.
[src:apple-butter/allington-pippin] This apple is conical shaped and its outer skin is combined from flashy colours of red and orange, flushed and striped, with some russeting.
[src:apple-butter/allington-pippin] Its special mellowing to sharp fruit candy or pineapple flavour is appreciated in multipurpose use: cooking, fresh eating and flavourful apple cider.
[src:apple-butter/allington-pippin] Allington is rather a strong fruit, it has a good storage record of three months or more, and keeps shape in cooking.
[src:apple-butter/allington-pippin] 'Allington Pippin' has a biennial bearing tendency, flowers are partially self-sterile, mid season; harvest period is late.
[src:apple-butter/allington-pippin] The tree is average on general tendency to diseases, but blossom is susceptible to frost.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Its colour, juice content, sweetness, and overall flavour have made the Ambrosia one of the most purchased apples in numerous countries.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] The Ambrosia apple tree has an upright growth pattern, varying on soil quality, rootstock, environment, and management.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] The tree develops lateral branches, requiring pruning to maintain vigour and fruit size.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] In the first two years of growth, significant tree training is needed to assure well-angled fruiting branches and productivity.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia apple trees are suitable for dense planting, have high yields, and require little pruning during the winter.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Pollinating partners of the Ambrosia include the Cortland, Fuji, and Granny Smith.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] The fruit is medium to large, 6.8–7.5 cm (2.7–3.0 in) in diameter, weighing about 215 grams (0.474 lb), and has mostly red, glossy colouration, with yellow patches.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] It has cream-coloured, firm, and juicy texture, with a mild and sweet flavour reminiscent of pear and low acidity, with the flesh resisting oxidation, making it suitable for salads and fresh fruit displays.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] These apples flower in the mid-to-late blossom period, and are harvested in mid-to-late season (mid-September in its native Similkameen Valley of British Columbia; September–October in Ontario, mid-October in Quebec).
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia apples produce a low amount of ethylene, not displaying the usual climacteric rise at harvest.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Accordingly, internal ethylene concentrations do not indicate accurate fruit maturity, whereas skin colour and starch staining charts are commonly used for optimal harvest and standardization of fruit quality.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Orchard irrigation conditions appear to be a factor causing soft scald and reduced quality of Ambrosia apples during storage.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Derived from a chance seedling, the Ambrosia is suspected to be a cross of the Starking Delicious and the Golden Delicious because those apples existed in the orchard where the Ambrosia was discovered growing.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia is a "club" variety of apple, in which a cultivar is patented by an organization that sets quality standards and provides marketing, while production is limited to club members.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Centralized control allowed limitation of color variation to pink/red, as the variety would colour differently in warmer climates.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] The patent expired in Canada in 2015, in the United States in 2017, and in Chile in 2021.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] It remains active in many other countries until as late as 2034.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] While under patent in Canada, the Mennell family obtained plant breeders rights, and all growers were allowed, paying a royalty of CA$2–3.75 per tree planting.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] While under patent in the US, growers paid the lesser of US$1 per tree planting or US$1,000 per acre, and a US$1,000 franchise fee.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] The Ambrosia Gold is marketed as the premium version of this variety.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Ambrosia is most commonly cultivated in British Columbia, where it was the third most-produced apple in 2016.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] By the mid 2020s, British Columbia continues to take the lead in production, followed by Ontario and Nova Scotia.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] Alongside the Honeycrisp and Gala, the Ambrosia has risen in prominence among Canadian farmers and consumers at the expense of the Red Delicious.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] In the United States, the majority of Ambrosia apples are harvested in Washington State and New York.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] This variety is also grown in Chile, New Zealand, the Netherlands, and Italy, among other countries.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] In the early 21st century, it is one of the most popular apple varieties in Canada and the United States, especially in the South and Midwest.
[src:apple-butter/ambrosia-apple] It has also found success in the Asian market, notably Vietnam.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The roots of apple butter lie in Limburg (Belgium and the Netherlands) and Rhineland (Germany), conceived during the Middle Ages, when the first monasteries (with large orchards) appeared.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The production of the butter was a perfect way to conserve part of the fruit production of the monasteries in that region, at a time when almost every village had its own apple-butter producers.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The production of apple butter was also a popular way of using apples in colonial America, well into the 19th century.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The product contains no actual dairy butter; the term *butter* refers only to the butter-like thick, soft consistency, and apple butter's use as a spread for breads.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Sometimes seasoned with cinnamon, clove, and other spices, apple butter is usually spread on bread, used as a side dish, an ingredient in baked goods, or as a condiment.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter may also be used on sandwiches to add an interesting flavor, but is not as commonly used as in historical times.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Vinegar or lemon juice is sometimes mixed in while cooking to provide a small amount of tartness to the usually sweet apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The Pennsylvania Dutch often include apple butter as part of their traditional 'seven sweets and seven sours' dinner table array.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In areas of the American South, the production of apple butter is a family event, due to the large amount of labor necessary to produce apple butter in large quantities.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Traditionally, apple butter was prepared in large copper kettles outside.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Large paddles were used to stir the apples, and family members would take turns stirring.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In Appalachian cuisine, apple butter was the only type of fruit preserve normally rendered into fruit leather.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In Europe, an apple butter is traditionally made which is closer to dense syrup, in the Netherlands (known as *appelstroop*, meaning *apple syrup*) and in Germany (known as *Apfelkraut*) and frequently eaten on bread with (or without) thinly sliced cheese and with *Sauerbraten*.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] A sweeter version, made using pears, as well as apples, is more popular in Belgium, where it is known as *sirop de Liège*.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Other than in Benelux and the Rhineland, apple syrup is a minority taste in Western Europe (in Germany, outside of the Rhineland, it is generally sold in health food shops), and a similar food is produced in francophone Switzerland, where it is known as *vin cuit*.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Russian Пови́дло (from Czech *povidla*, or Polish *powidła* or *powidło*) is prepared by the reduction of fruit puree with some sugar and sometimes spices.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The final product should contain no more than 34% of moisture and about 60% of sugar.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The most popular one is made from apples, but *povidlo* is also made from apricots, cherries, prunes, pears, and cranberries.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Polish powidła is made from fresh purple plums with the addition of sugar.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In Jersey, in the Channel Islands, apple butter is known as *black butter* or *lé nièr beurre* and includes liquorice as an ingredient.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In Northern Ireland it is now produced under the name "Irish Black Butter" in Co.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The possibly apocryphal story is that it was Scots-Irish immigrants who introduced the recipe to the Appalachians.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In Japan, apple butter often contains actual butter and is considerably lighter in color, typically a shade of yellow.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter can be used as a fat substitute in reduced-fat or fat-free cooking, as well as vegan recipes.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Different types of apples can be used for the production of apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apples are chosen based on their physical and chemical properties – such as hardness, sweetness, acidity/tartness, etc.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Soft apples are often chosen for the production of apple butter because they can be broken down more easily and faster when cooked.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] These types of apples include: McIntosh (soft, creamy), Cortland (soft, sweet-and-tart, all-purpose), Granny Smith (tartness sweetens upon cooking, ideal complement to savory and salty foods).
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apples are first selected based on ripeness, texture, natural sweetness and tartness/acidity.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Some of these apples are pressed into fresh apple cider, while the rest are peeled and cored, then wholly steamed and cooked into apple puree.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The freshly pressed apple cider and cooked apple puree are added to a large steam vat.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Small amounts of sodium bicarbonate are added to the mixture in order to reduce acidity and help bring out sweetness from the natural fructose available in the apples.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The mixture will then be boiled during the evaporation process, allowing the volume to reduce to one seventh.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The end product will be a concentrated mixture used as apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter is typically packaged in the same way whether it is prepared in a factory setting or made at home.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] It can be packaged mechanically in jars or cans through the use of machinery.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter is a product created as a means of preserving apples.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Due to its high acidity, high sugar content and low amounts of free water, an opened package can be kept for months at room temperature without spoiling.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Nevertheless, there are numerous methods that can be used for the storage of apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] No method is 100% dependable, as there is always a chance of the presence of bacteria or other microorganisms within the food itself, on the storage equipment or in the storage facility.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Typically, the jars are sterilized before packaging to ensure no harmful microorganisms or bacteria will infect the product, causing it to spoil.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Ideally, jars are sterilized using a combination of high temperature heating and ensuring a tight seal.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apples are a high acid food, with a pH below 4.6.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Therefore, the apple butter can be placed in hot jars without chances of compromising quality of the product.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The main sources of spoilage, molds, yeasts and enzymes, are killed at the temperatures reached in the hot water bath during the sterilization process for cans and jars.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The spoilage microorganisms in acid foods can be destroyed in a small amount of time at temperatures below that of boiling water, so there is little risk of microorganisms appearing in the food product itself.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Freezing jars of apple butter can help to maintain quality and inhibit bacterial growth.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] This storage method does not destroy pre-existing microorganisms that may be present in the product, so it is important to be wary when consuming previously frozen product.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Applying high temperatures over a specified period of time can not only aid in the sterilization of the jars or cans used in packaging, but it can help maximize the storage time of the apple butter or other products.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Boiling the jars will remove the oxygen remaining in the jar, which forms a tight seal between the lid and the rim.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The heat used for this method of canning can be sufficient to kill bacterial cells found in the food.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Only high-acid food with a pH of 4.6 or less can be processed using the boiling water bath method.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] This is because high-acid foods prevent the growth of spores of the bacterium *Clostridium botulinum*, which cannot be killed by boiling.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Foods with a pH of more than 4.6 can allow the spores to grow.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Similar to the boiling process, vacuum sealing jars or cans of apple butter can remove remaining oxygen in the jar, forming a tight seal.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The vacuuming process can be done in both a large-scale factory manner or at home with a mechanical vacuum sealer.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Special devices, such as a vacuum pack sealer, can be fitted with specific jar attachments to fit over the lid of a jar and create a secure fit.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Low-acid foods can be processed in a pressure canner to get rid of the risk of botulism; however, this treatment is not necessary for high-acid foods such as apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter does not require sterilization at extremely high temperatures to reach optimum storage and maintain quality, so the pressure canning process is not typically used for this product.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The preservation of apple butter involves application of several food science concepts, including controlling the temperature, water activity, and level of acidity in the product.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Thermal processing not only helps produce texture and flavor characteristic to apple butter but is also a common way of sterilizing food products.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] It is a critical step in minimizing the potential growth of spoilage-causing and illness-causing microorganisms in the product.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] As a result of thermal processing and the softening of the apples, the presence of air bubbles can be minimized during canning.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Refrigeration is a way of preserving apple butter after thermal processing.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Though it is not a method which eliminates microorganisms, it is a method to decrease the rate at which microorganisms grow.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Opened jars of apple butter may last a year if kept under low-temperature conditions.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] With refrigeration, the quality of apple butter may still decrease over time.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Aside from controlling the temperature, regulation of the water activity in apple butter may also preserve the quality of apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Water present in foods may exist in two types: bound water and free water.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Bound water refers to water molecules that are attached to other molecules, making them unable to participate in chemical reactions or be utilized by microorganisms to contribute to their growth.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Free water refers to water molecules free to perform the above functions, and should be decreased to achieve a longer preservation period.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The addition of sugar to apple butter allows more binding with the free water molecules and thereby decreases the amount of free water to support microbial growth.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Lowering the pH level of apple butter may also help decrease the rate of spoilage.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Acidity in foods creates a less favorable environment for the survival of microorganisms, thus inhibiting the growth of bacteria and molds.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Foods that have a pH of less than 4.6 are considered high-acid foods, and apples in general have a pH of 3.7.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Some recipes may include the addition of vinegar as a way to further bring down the pH and preserve the quality of the end product.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Sometimes, commercial brands of apple butter can be found with other ingredients and food additives.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] High fructose corn syrup is a preservative that has a high level of acidity and is often used by manufacturers in the preservation of food products, including apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Sodium benzoate, an additive allowed under the Canadian food regulation, is capable of inhibiting the growth of fungi and has been used as a preservative in apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] It is possible to observe spoilage in apple butter if the end product is not properly sterilized during the canning process, allowing microorganisms to survive and grow in the container.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Lack of refrigeration may also speed up the rate of spoilage of apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Slight deterioration in quality happens with time even if the product is refrigerated, and does not pose a threat to the consumer.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Some indicators for change in quality include the change of color and smell.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] However, apple butter should be discarded if there are clear signs of spoilage, such as when mold is found on the product surface.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Even prior to apple butter preparation, the quality of apples should be taken into consideration since it has been reported to correspond to the level of patulin, a type of toxin produced by molds, present in apples.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Studies have also shown that a longer period of heat treatment can reduce the levels of patulin present in the product.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The nutritional value of apple butter varies quite a bit based on the recipe used to prepare that particular product.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The ingredient list can be as simple as just two ingredients to a much more complicated mixture of foods.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Although the ingredients may vary, which changes the nutritional value of the apple butter, the two main things that stand out to consumers on the nutritional facts table are the amount of carbohydrates and the amount of sugar that the apple butter contains.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] For 1 tablespoon the amount of carbohydrates is about 4–15 grams and the sugar content is about 4–10 grams.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter is not a good source for iron, calcium, vitamin A, vitamin B, though it contains a small amount of vitamin C.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Although all the recipes vary, the main ingredients in all apple butters are apples and apple juice.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In commercial brands of apple butter, the type of apples used is not specified, but in certain homemade recipes they specify what types of apples to use.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Commercial brands tend to use corn syrup in their apple butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In homemade apple butter, sugar or brown sugar are more frequently used.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter may be a healthier choice of spread than other breakfast spreads, but would not be considered to be healthy, as it does not provide very many nutrients.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In the Netherlands, appelstroop is widely recognised as a good source of iron, a dietary element in which modern diets are frequently considered deficient.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] There is a widespread view that the iron content arises from the interaction of the acid in the apples with the metal of vessels in which the appelstroop is prepared and packaged.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] However, commercially sold appelstroop is often sold in paper- or plastic-based containers (or, in Germany, glass jars).
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Well into the fifties, the traditional cooking pots used for the preparation of appelstroop were generally of copper.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Regardless of how appelstroop originally gained its reputation as a source of dietary iron, the iron content (10–20 mg per 100 g) in typical factory-produced product is boosted by the sugar beet, which is included with apples in the approximate ratio of 30:70.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter is at low risk for spreading food-borne disease.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The way that apple butter is packaged is very similar to that of jams.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter is stored in glass jars, which allow light to enter the container therefore their shelf-life is less than that of food canned in steel cans.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The preservation technique used to preserve apple butter is called canning.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Canning is a process where pre-packaged food is exposed to moist heat of at least 121 °C for a certain amount of time in order to kill microorganisms that cause spoilage and disease.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Although apple butter is at low risk for food-borne disease if canned improperly, especially when being made at home, the product may grow dangerous microorganisms.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] If the apple butter is improperly canned, *Clostridium botulinum* can survive and multiply in the jar.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] This germ produces a toxin that can seriously harm an individual or in some cases even cause death.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Makers of apple butter need to verify that the jars are properly sealed and that the heat treatment is used on the jars of apple butter for a sufficient amount of time in order to kill all microorganisms and prevent the product from contamination through the air of the outside environment.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Once the jar is unsealed, the product must be refrigerated to slow down or inhibit the growth of microorganisms that cause spoilage.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple butter and apple sauce also have different uses.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Popular ways of using apple butter include as a condiment or a spread for pastries and pie fillings.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] It is also a very popular spread for pancakes in the low countries.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] It can also be used as a healthier alternative for oil, shortening, or butter.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Some people also enjoy using it to marinate meat, or pairing it with cooked meat and cheeses such as cheddar, brie or chevre.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple sauce, in contrast, is usually served on its own or as a side dish for a variety of dishes.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] During the preparation, apples are cored for apple sauces but not for apple butter, allowing it to have a much stronger apple taste.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] The two also differ in cooking time; apple sauce just needs to be cooked until the apples are soft enough to be pureed, while apple butter needs to be cooked until the apples brown, break down and thicken.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] As a result of its long cooking time, apple butter is a much darker, caramel brown color, while apple sauce is usually a lighter golden color.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple sauce has a more liquid consistency while apple butter is thicker and is more spreadable.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] In various locations across the United States, the production of apple butter is associated with a community event, most often occurring in the fall at the end of the apple-harvest season.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] At many of these events, apple butter is cooked on-site in the traditional method, using huge copper kettles over open fires that are stirred for hours.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Apple Butter Makin' Days has been held on the courthouse square in Mount Vernon, Missouri, each October since 1967.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Kimmswick, Missouri, and Berkeley Springs, West Virginia, each have an annual apple butter festival, as well.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Grand Rapids, Ohio, also celebrates with an Apple Butter Fest on October 12.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] There is also an Apple Butter Stir Off held on the first weekend in October in Belpre, Ohio.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Wellesley, Ontario, has an annual Apple Butter and Cheese Festival on the last Saturday in September.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Fenner Nature Center in Lansing, Michigan, also has an annual Apple Butter Festival on the third weekend of October.
[src:apple-butter/apple-butter] Oak Glen, California, has an Apple Butter Festival in November on Thanksgiving Weekend as part of the close of their official Apple Harvest Season.
